"Moslener U., Requate T.","The dynamics of optimal abatement strategies for multiple pollutants-An illustration in the Greenhouse",2009,"Ecological Economics","68","5",,"1521","1534",,,10.1016/j.ecolecon.2008.10.010,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-60249089958&partnerID=40&md5=695077abc8a43afefc5df10196848abc","Center for European Economic Research (ZEW), Mannheim, Germany; Department of Economics, University of Kiel, Olshausenstrasse 40, D-24098 Kiel, Germany","Moslener, U., Center for European Economic Research (ZEW), Mannheim, Germany; Requate, T., Department of Economics, University of Kiel, Olshausenstrasse 40, D-24098 Kiel, Germany","We investigate optimal abatement strategies for cumulative and interacting pollutants. We show that different decay rates can cause non-monotonic behavior in the optimal paths of emissions, the aggregate level of pollution, and even the relative optimal price for emissions. This contrasts strikingly with the case of a single pollutant. The results are illustrated by numerical simulations, first for instructive fictitious and second for more realistic parameters mimicking the greenhouse problem. The results add to the skepticism existing about whether the concept of global warming potential is a useful indicator for the optimal relative abatement of different GHGs over time. In fact, we show that a constant index suitable for comparing dynamically different pollutants with respect to their economic harmfulness does not exist. © 2008 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Decay rates; Global warming potential; Greenhouse gases; Multi-gas assessment; Pollutant interaction; Radiative forcing","abatement cost; emissions trading; global warming; numerical model; pollution control; radiative forcing",,,,,,"Alcamo, J., Shaw, R., Hordijk, L., (1990) The RAINS Model of Acidification: Science and Strategies in Europe, , Kluwer Academic publishers, Dordrecht, The Netherlands; Cansier, A., Cansier, D., Umweltstandards bei Unsicherheit aus Entscheidungstheoretischer Sicht (1999) ""Umweltrisikopolitik"" (Zeitschrift für Angewandte Umweltforschung, Special Issue 10/1999), pp. 157-171. , Hansjürgens B. (Ed), Analytica, Berlin; Chiang, A.C., (1992) Elements of Dynamic Optimization, , McGraw-Hill, Singapore; Cline, W.R., (1992) The Economics of Global Warming, , Institute for International Economics, Washington, DC; Criqui, P., Russ, P., Deybe, D., Impacts of multi-gas strategies for greenhouse gas abatement: insights from a partial equilibrium model (2006) The Energy Journal, pp. 251-273. , (special Issue on ""Multi-Greenhouse Gas Mitigation and Climate Policy""); Endres, A., Environmental policy with pollutant interaction (1985) Public Goods and Public Allocation Policy, Frankfurt/M, , Pethig R. (Ed); Falk, I., Mendelsohn, R., The economics of controlling stock pollutants: an efficient strategy for greenhouse gases (1993) Journal of Environmental Economics and Management, 25, pp. 76-88; Farzin, Y.H., Tahvonen, O., Global carbon cycle and the optimal time path of a carbon tax (1996) Oxford Economic Papers, 48, pp. 515-536; Feichtinger, G., Hartl, R.F., (1986) Optimale Kontrolle ökonomischer Prozesse, , Walter de Gruyter, Berlin; Finlayson-Pitts, B.J., Pitts, J.N., (2000) Chemistry of the Upper and Lower Atmosphere, , Academic Press, San Diego; Houghton, J.T., Jenkins, G.J., Ephraums, J.J., (1990) Climate Change: The IPCC Scientific Assessment, , Working Group 1, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, U.K; Kandlikar, M., The relative role of trace gas emissions in greenhouse abatement policies (1995) Energy Policy, 23 (10), pp. 879-883; Kandlikar, M., Indices for comparing greenhouse gas emissions: integrating science and economics (1996) Energy Economics, 18, pp. 265-281; Klaassen, G., Trade-offs in sulfur emission trading in Europe (1995) Environmental and Resource Economics, 5 (2), pp. 9-27; Maier-Raimer, E., Hasselmann, K., Transport and storage of CO2 in the ocean an inorganic ocean-circu